1. If Statement
   we Use 'if' to specify a block of code to be executed, if a specified condition is true

  if (condition) {
  // some codes
  }
eg..let color; 
If (mode === "dark-mode") {
 color = "black";
}


2. else Statement
 we Use 'else' to specify a block of code to be executed, if a specified condition is false...

//sample code
let age = prompt ( "what is your age")
if ( age >= 18 ) {
    console.log("you can drive")
} else {
    alert ("you cannot drive")
} 


3. else if Statement
we use 'else if' to specify a new condition to test, if the first condition is false

//sample code
let age = prompt ( "what is your age")
if ( age >= 18 ) {
    console.log("you can drive")
} else if( age < 18 ) {
console.log (" you cannot drivr")
} else {
    alert ("this is invalid age")
} 

4. Switch Statement
Use 'switch' to specify many alternative blocks of code to be executed


